{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478107"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:09:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:09:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15722"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15722"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.06,0.52,0.03,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8413"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47847"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"4805"},{"type":"tags","id":"9589"},{"type":"tags","id":"9590"},{"type":"tags","id":"11101"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46005"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-week-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with poor feeding and lethargy for 24 hours. She was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. She has ambiguous genitalia. Blood tests reveal sodium 128 mmol/L (135-145), potassium 6.5 mmol/L (3.5-5.0), and glucose 2.8 mmol/L (3.5-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following enzyme deficiencies is most likely to be responsible for this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["17-alpha-hydroxylase","11-beta-hydroxylase","21-hydroxylase","3-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase","17-beta-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with features of congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH), characterised by ambiguous genitalia, electrolyte disturbances, and hypoglycaemia. The most common cause is \u003Cstrong\u003E21-hydroxylase\u003C/strong\u003E deficiency, accounting for over 90% of cases. This enzyme deficiency results in impaired cortisol and aldosterone synthesis, leading to salt wasting and increased ACTH production, which drives excess androgen production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other enzymes are involved in different pathways in hormone synthesis, and knowledge of their exact roles is beyond the scope of medical student education. However, knowledge of 21-hydroxylase deficiency and it\u0027s role in the condition congenital adrenal hyperplasia is an important deficiency and condition of which to be aware.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Congenital adrenal hyperplasia can present with ambiguous genitalia, electrolyte disturbances, and hypoglycaemia.","21-hydroxylase deficiency accounts for over 90% of cases of congenital adrenal hyperplasia."],"references":["Momodu II, Lee B, Singh G. Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia. In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448098/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47847"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15722"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47847","links":